==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Literary
<hw>Lit"er*a*ry</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"⟦etil⟧r*⟦asl⟧*r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>litterarius</ets>, <ets>literarius</ets>,
fr. <ets>littera</ets>, <ets>litera</ets>, a letter: cf. F.
<ets>litt⟦eacute⟧raire</ets>. See <er>Letter</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to letters or literature;
pertaining to learning or learned men; <as>as, <ex>literary</ex> fame; a
<ex>literary</ex> history; <ex>literary</ex>
conversation.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has long outlived his century, the term commonly fixed as the
test of <qex>literary</qex> merit.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Versed in, or acquainted with, literature; occupied
with literature as a profession; connected with literature or with men
of letters; <as>as, a <ex>literary</ex> man</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the <qex>literary</qex> as well as fashionable world.</q>
<rj><qau>Mason.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Literary property</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Property
which consists in written or printed compositions.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>The exclusive right of publication as recognized and limited by
law.</cd></cs><--- e.g. a copyright -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Literate</ent>⟦br⟧
